</figure>
</p>

<p>&ldquo;Eighteen years old,&rdquo; I say and reach over to pat his back. This is a big year, I tell him. He&rsquo;s going to graduate from high school, maybe take more art classes at the center. He&rsquo;s making healthier choices, not cruising the park anymore.</p>

<p>&ldquo;No, I been there,&rdquo; Rodrigo says. &ldquo;Every day this week.&rdquo; He stares out at the highway.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Oh,&rdquo; I say. &ldquo;I thought you were trying to stop that.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rodrigo says he changed his mind and tells me about Rodney, a guy he met deep in the park. After having sex, they decided to offer older men blow jobs for twenty dollars.</p>

<p>Rodrigo pauses, as if waiting for a reaction. I ask if he did it, and he says Rodney did once, but he was there. Things got out of control quickly. The man was larger than them and became aggressive, wanting more than a blow job. Before Rodrigo knew what was happening, Rodney pulled out a knife and screamed for the man to hand over his cash. The man threw them all his money but said he was going to catch them and skin them alive. Scared, Rodrigo scrambled away.</p>

<p>I ask if anyone was hurt. When he answers no, I&rsquo;m relieved. I&rsquo;m trying to figure out a way not to report this. &ldquo;What the hell is going on?&rdquo; I ask.</p>

<p>He&rsquo;s looking out the side window, but I can tell he&rsquo;s crying. &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; he says, wiping his eyes with his wrist. &ldquo;Sometimes it&rsquo;s like I can&rsquo;t feel nothing unless I do something extreme.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rodrigo begs me not to say anything to Rebecca. He feels guilty about what happened. It won&rsquo;t happen again. He just needed to tell someone. He asks me to promise not to tell anyone.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t move my eyes from the road. Being held at knife point: I wonder how many times I&rsquo;ve narrowly escaped that situation in the park.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;m worried Rodrigo will end up in prison, or dead, if he continues on in this direction, but he begs me to keep his secret. His face is blotchy from crying. &ldquo;Please,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;Promise.&rdquo;</p>

<p>A long silence builds up between us. I want to tell him that I know what it&rsquo;s like &mdash; the search for something outside himself to make him feel whole. I&rsquo;m desperate to find a way for Rodrigo to know that I understand without revealing my own secret.</p>

<p>&ldquo;OK,&rdquo; I say. &ldquo;I promise.&rdquo; A deep regret fills me as soon as the words leave my mouth.</p>

<p class="dropcap">Back at the group home, alone in the office, I pace. I want to disappear, to slink away into some obliterated shell of myself. I stop in front of the medicine cabinet and stare at its reflective metal door. Before I know what I&rsquo;m doing, I unlock it and pull out a bottle of Xanax prescribed to a former resident. When focusing on the work at the group home, I&rsquo;m able to forget that I lead a double life. Here I can play the part of a healthy residential counselor, keeping hidden the portions of myself that don&rsquo;t fit the image. But I can feel my secrets blighting my body like a disease. I don&rsquo;t want Rodrigo becoming a practiced liar like me.</p>

<p>I pop off the lid of the Xanax bottle and swallow two tablets. They scrape my throat like tacks. Then I sit down at Rebecca&rsquo;s desk, impatient for the sedative to grip me, and I take the program phone directory from the top drawer of the filing cabinet. I find the extension I&rsquo;m looking for and glance up to make sure there&rsquo;s no one outside the door. It&rsquo;s my duty to tell someone, for Rodrigo&rsquo;s safety. My voice hushed, I leave a message on Steve&rsquo;s voice mail, telling him about the new development in Rodrigo&rsquo;s behavior.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">A week later, when it&rsquo;s time for Rodrigo&rsquo;s service-plan review, Rebecca asks me to be the representative from the 401. I&rsquo;m supposed to talk about how he&rsquo;s adjusted to the program. I&rsquo;ve been given a questionnaire to fill out, rating him on his willingness to follow rules: 1 indicating low functionality; 5, high functionality. If I were to score myself on cleanliness, doing chores, or maintaining an orderly room the way I have to with Rodrigo, I&rsquo;d fail. And if my personal life were found out, I&rsquo;d be put on &ldquo;alarm.&rdquo;</p>

<p>I wonder what Rodrigo would say if he could peer into my apartment window at night and witness me, alone in my mess of dirty laundry and empty liquor bottles: <em>You supposed to be telling me how to live</em> my <em>life? Least I got one.</em> Or maybe he&rsquo;d look at my squalor and, embarrassed, slowly shake his head.</p>

<p>Rodrigo is sitting at the head of the table, flanked by his mother and Steve. Jessica is there. Rebecca too. A social worker rushes in late, wearing a suit and tie, finishing a call on his cellphone.</p>

<p>For the next forty-five minutes Rodrigo listens to us tell his life story. Steve says that, despite Rodrigo&rsquo;s long absence from school before entering foster care, his teachers report that he&rsquo;s catching up. If he continues at this pace, he&rsquo;ll be able to graduate with his class. The independent-living specialist talks about Rodrigo&rsquo;s art classes and his participation in the center&rsquo;s youth program. There&rsquo;s discussion about part-time employment or an internship. I talk about how Rodrigo&rsquo;s been bathing regularly, keeping his room tidy, and socializing. Rodrigo follows rules well, I say, and is likable when he&rsquo;s not provoking the other residents. I mention his successes and a few stumbles along the way. Looking over at Rodrigo, I say that he has a lot of potential.</p>

<p>Steve concludes the meeting by stating the agency&rsquo;s goals for Rodrigo over the next six months: high-school graduation, art classes, and a part-time job. Just as we&rsquo;re about to leave, Steve says, &ldquo;We have one more order of business to discuss.&rdquo; He looks at Rodrigo. &ldquo;I hear you&rsquo;ve been busy in the park again.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rodrigo&rsquo;s eyes are fixed on the table in front of him. The room quiets.</p>

<p>&ldquo;With all this success, why do you go to the park and have sex with strangers? You&rsquo;re putting your life at risk. You know that, don&rsquo;t you?&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rodrigo nods slightly. His mother&rsquo;s face is expressionless.</p>

<p>&ldquo;And I heard that this time you were asking for money. You have too much going for you to start prostituting.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rodrigo glances up at me.</p>

<p>I can&rsquo;t look at him. My eyes scan the questionnaire, the numbers that approximate his ability to live a successful life.</p>

<p>Steve tells Rodrigo he&rsquo;s going to be put on alarm, then continues to talk about the park. &ldquo;Is that the life you want to live?&rdquo; he asks.</p>

<p>&ldquo;No,&rdquo; Rodrigo whispers.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p class="dropcap">The van sputters as it idles. Rodrigo and I sit silently, looking at his neighborhood. Boys in oversized <span class="smallcaps">T</span>-shirts and drooping jeans gather on the courtyard benches. Two mothers who look younger than Rodrigo prop their babies on their hips and lean against an old Buick. Reggaeton music blasts and Puerto Rican flags flap from open apartment windows.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t want Rodrigo to get out of the van. He&rsquo;s about to take a course of action that could destroy any chance he has at a moderately normal life. Two days after his review he announced that he&rsquo;d decided to sign himself out of care. He claimed it had nothing to do with the review; he needed to be back with his family. Rodrigo showed me the letter he&rsquo;d written the judge, to clear up this mess he&rsquo;d created.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I made it all up,&rdquo; he said boldly. &ldquo;John never touched me.&rdquo; In the letter he confessed that he&rsquo;d lied to get revenge against his brother for abandoning the family.</p>

<p>I drum my fingers on the steering wheel and watch two boys in the courtyard sneak up behind a girl, pour a drink on her, and run.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;m wary of Rodrigo&rsquo;s sudden reversal of his story. The accusations of abuse rang so true, I rarely thought to question them. I can&rsquo;t help feeling it was my breach of trust that prompted Rodrigo to alter his story and leave the program.</p>

<p>&ldquo;You can still change your mind,&rdquo; I say. &ldquo;Just stay until you finish high school.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rodrigo smiles and shakes his head. &ldquo;This is home,&rdquo; he says.</p>

<p>I know he feels I&rsquo;ve betrayed him &mdash; like his family, like the system &mdash; even if he won&rsquo;t admit it.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Or at least a trial discharge,&rdquo; I say. &ldquo;You&rsquo;ll be at home but with the support of the program. You can sign out as soon as you graduate.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Rodrigo looks at the fight that&rsquo;s broken out between one of the boys and the doused girl. She takes off her earrings and throws them at his feet. People start to gather. The girl swings wildly at the boy. The crowd grows.</p>

<p>&ldquo;They my family. I belong here,&rdquo; he says as the boy pushes the girl, and she falls, blocked from view by the spectators.</p>

<p>Rodrigo shakes my hand, then gathers his backpack and sketch pad. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll come by the house sometime.&rdquo;</p>

<p>We both know that&rsquo;s not going to happen.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Finish school, Rodrigo.&rdquo;</p>

<p>He nods and gets out of the van. &ldquo;Wish me luck,&rdquo; he says, then walks away.</p>

<p>He passes through the courtyard, past the fight that has all but ended, past the boys on their benches. One of them calls out, &ldquo;Puto sucio!&rdquo; and they all laugh. Rodrigo smiles at them weakly, tucks his sketch pad under his arm, and opens the battered metal door to the building. He looks back before entering and gives me that big-cheeked grin of his when he sees I&rsquo;m still here, watching.</p>

<hr />
<p><em>Names and identifying details have been changed to protect privacy.</em></p>

<p class="text-right"><em>&mdash; Ed.</em></p>
