			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="580">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I read Ryan Berg&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4637">Tick Tick Boom</a>&rdquo; [March 2012] during some downtime while working the night shift, and it left me reeling. Then I turned a couple of pages to find &ldquo;Underneath the Armor.&rdquo;</p>

<p>My son was an army ranger who served in Afghanistan and was left with 100 percent disability due to post-traumatic stress disorder. He was shot and killed by a police officer last November in Farmington, Maine.</p>

<p>I took a few deep breaths, read these marines&rsquo; stories, and looked hard into their faces. Reading it with others around was a test of my emotional strength.</p>

<p>When I was done, I walked down the hall and cried. I cried for the loss of my son, for these and all soldiers, and for a world fixated on violence.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Ruth Crowley<br>Portland, Oregon</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="581">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I have long appreciated the ability of <em>The Sun</em>&rsquo;s contributors to put into words the contradictions inherent in efforts to create justice in an unjust world.</p>

<p>After reading Ryan Berg&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;Tick Tick Boom,&rdquo; however, I find myself angry over the author&rsquo;s lack of effort to treat his own addiction and the high cost of his neglect for the gay youth named Rodrigo, who lived at the group home where Berg worked. I do not respect an author who seems to invest more time in wordsmithing than in seeking therapy and expressing his vulnerability where it matters most &mdash; not in the pages of a magazine his residents will never read but in person to Rodrigo himself, who needed authenticity, not platitudes.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jessica Tartaro<br>Austin, Texas</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="582">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Ryan Berg should have told Rodrigo that he had to report his risky behavior. He should have dealt with whatever reaction the boy might have had, no matter how difficult. To betray Rodrigo&rsquo;s confidence, no matter that the law insists on it, was a terrible act. I realize Berg was trying to save the boy&rsquo;s life, but his actions only put Rodrigo in more danger by sending him away from supervision. Berg says he will continue to watch Rodrigo as the story ends. I hope he does.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Rich Quatrone<br>Spring Lake, New Jersey</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="516">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I imagine that you have received a number of letters criticizing you for publishing Ryan Berg&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4637">Tick Tick Boom</a>&rdquo; [March 2012]. I&rsquo;m sure that some people had a problem with the explicit details, while others didn&rsquo;t like the subject matter in general. I found the essay quite moving, and I thank you for taking a chance on it. As a gay man, I enjoy seeing work by gay writers in my favorite magazine, even when the lives on display are very different from my own.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Peter Wilsnack<br>Seattle, Washington</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
